        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5922.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from A. R. Wallace, 24 February 1868</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The display of plumage by the male <hi rend="italic">Rupicola crocea</hi> (now <hi rend="italic">R. rupicola</hi>, the Guianan cock-of-the-rock) is described in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 2: 87–8. For CD’s discussions of hummingbirds and birds of paradise, see <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp. 86 and 88.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5848.xml" resp="#automat">letter from A. R. Wallace, 7 February 1868</ref> and n. 4.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">On Wallace’s theory of protective coloration, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5852.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Albany Hancock, 8 February 1868</ref>, n. 3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_317.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henry Walter Bates</ref>; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5893.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from H. W. Bates, 18 February 1868</ref> and n. 1.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">Wallace had published two papers on the orang-utan in the <hi rend="italic">Annals and Magazine of Natural History</hi> (A. R. Wallace 1856a and 1856b).</note>
